    <exercise id="fs-id1546485" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1933588">
      <para id="import-auto-id3353285">The activities of <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mtext>131</m:mtext></m:msup><m:mtext>I</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> and

<m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mtext>123</m:mtext></m:msup><m:mtext>I</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> used in thyroid scans are given in <link target-id="eip-909"/> to be 50 and

<m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>70 μ</m:mtext><m:mn>Ci</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>, respectively. Find and compare the masses of

<m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mtext>131</m:mtext></m:msup><m:mtext>I</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> and

<m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mtext>123</m:mtext></m:msup><m:mtext>I</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> in such scans, given their respective half-lives are 8.04 d and 13.2 h. The masses are so small that the radioiodine is usually mixed with stable iodine as a carrier to ensure normal chemistry and distribution in the body.</para></problem></exercise>

    <exercise id="fs-id2973764" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id3205488">
      <para id="import-auto-id1488236">(a) Neutron activation of sodium, which is 100%<m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mtext>23</m:mtext></m:msup><m:mtext>Na</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>, produces

<m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mtext>24</m:mtext></m:msup><m:mtext>Na</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>, which is used in some heart scans, as seen in <link target-id="eip-909"/>. The equation for the reaction is

<m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mtext>23</m:mtext></m:msup><m:mrow><m:mtext>Na</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:mi>n</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">→</m:mo>
<m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mtext>24</m:mtext></m:msup><m:mrow><m:mtext>Na</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">+</m:mo><m:mi>γ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>. Find its energy output, given the mass of

<m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mtext>24</m:mtext></m:msup><m:mtext>Na</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> is 23.990962 u.</para><para id="import-auto-id1617247">(b) What mass of <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msup><m:mrow/><m:mtext>24</m:mtext></m:msup><m:mtext>Na</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> produces the needed 5.0-mCi activity, given its half-life is 15.0 h?</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-id3007553">
    <para id="import-auto-id2005836">(a) 6.958 MeV</para>
    <para id="import-auto-id3181786">(b) <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>5</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>7</m:mn><m:mo stretchy="false">×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mtext>10</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>g</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math></para></solution>
    </exercise>
